1. Quick Start Guide
Follow these steps to verify functionality in under 2 minutes:

Requirements: Ensure the Dynamic Storage and GameplayTags plugins are enabled in Edit > Plugins.

Set Data: In any Actor/Animation Blueprint, add a Set Storage node. Connect an "Integer" variable as an example to the Value/In pin and select Tag in the Tag field.
Note:- Always remember while using Set Storage node that the In pin of value or data should be connected by a physical pin not directly set to the pin itself.
For example:- Let suppose we are storing a float type value so rather than setting value direct to the pin, get a unreal engine Make Literal Float and connect that out pin to the Set Storage InPin

Get Data: Add a Get Storage node elsewhere in the graph. Select TagKey in the Tag field.
Note:- The auto detect function for outpin of Get Storage node only works in blueprint and only when a Set Storage node is used.

Confirm: Now, whenever you select a correct/valid tag and if it exist in storage, the pin will automatically turn according to data. You can use a print node to see the stored value in actual.Compile and Play to see the stored value on your screen.

Note:- Here, we don't need to physically wire the tag pin. Only need to physically wire the in/value pin in Set Storage node
And the in/value pin and outpin of Set Storage and Get Storage nodes respectively should not be wildcard otherwise it will throw the warning and the system will not work

Work system in C++
1. Add a "DynamicStorage" dependency in project.build.cs
2. include a header "DynamicStorageRuntimeLibrary"
3. include a header for gameplaytag also named "GameplayTagContainer.h"
3. Use DynamicStorageRuntimeLibrary::SetValue<T>(FGameplayTag, Value); // syntax
4. Use DynamicStorageRuntimeLibrary::GetValue<T>(FGameplayTag); // syntax

Note:- This system works on runtime only

For Example:- Setting a float variable and SkeletalMesjh
DynamicStorageRuntimeLibrary::SetValue<float>(FGameplayTag::RequestGameplayTag(FName("Test.float"), 95.5f);
DynamicStorageRuntimeLibrary::SetValue<USkeletalMeshComponent>(FGameplayTag::RequestGameplayTag(FName("Test.SkeletalMeshComponent"), this->GetMesh());

Note:- Here this means ACharacter class actor.

// Now get the stored values
float FloatVal = DynamicStorageRuntimeLibrary::GetValue<float>(FGameplayTag::RequestGameplayTag(FName("Test.float"));
USkeletalMeshComponent* SMCVal = DynamicStorageRuntimeLibrary::GetValue<USkeletalMeshComponent>(FGameplayTag::RequestGameplayTag(FName("Test.SkeletalMeshComponent"));

Note:- this will work only when "Test.float" and "Test.SkeletalMeshComponent" is valid/added in unreal engine GameplayTagContainer

2. Overview
The Dynamic Storage System is a high-performance C++ plugin that eliminates the need for repetitive casting and complex variable management in Blueprints. Using custom K2Nodes, it allows for seamless storage and retrieval of various data types through a unified "Wildcard" interface.

3. Key Features
Wildcard Property Support: "Get Storage" and "Set Storage" nodes automatically adapt to the connected data type.

Zero-Boilerplate Logic: Reduces the need for manual casting or large "Switch on Type" structures.

Modular Architecture: Features separate Runtime and UncookedOnly (Editor) modules for optimized packaging.

Native Integration: Designed to behave like native Unreal Engine nodes with context-sensitive pinning.

4. Installation
Navigate to fab and install it (When available on fab)

5. Technical Specifications
Module Structure
DynamicStorage (Runtime): Handles core data containers and memory management.

DynamicStorageEditor (UncookedOnly): Contains K2Node logic and compiler instructions.

Supported Data Types
Primitives: Boolean, Byte, Integer, Int64, Float, Double.

Common Structs: Vector, Rotator, Transform.

Strings: FString, FName, FText.

Objects: UObject and Actor references.

Enums: Custom, Unreal built-in

6. Troubleshooting
Missing Nodes: Verify that the DynamicStorageEditor module is included in your .uplugin file.

